WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.880
Unfortunately, that was my talk abstract and title was a bit of a lie, I did not write

00:00:09.880 --> 00:00:14.200
this talk with an LLM, but I did make that abstract.

00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:20.080
So what I want to actually give you is kind of a no-bullshit guide to LLMs, and I think

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:25.040
there's a whole lot of bullshit about LLMs in the air, so my goal is to hopefully clear

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:34.840
a little bit of that, if my clicker works.

00:00:34.840 --> 00:00:40.439
And I think probably many of you have kind of like big feelings about AI, I certainly

00:00:40.439 --> 00:00:51.160
do, there's a lot, you know, if you read about AI, like on the one hand there's like so much

00:00:51.160 --> 00:01:00.200
unbridled optimism, and on the other so much like skepticism, and as you start to engage

00:01:00.200 --> 00:01:06.080
with it yourself, I think you kind of experience both of those emotions, because AI, LLMs can

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:15.480
seem both like incredibly, surprisingly intelligent and also incredibly, surprisingly stupid as

00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:16.480
well.

00:01:16.480 --> 00:01:25.599
So I'll show you a few examples of that, but I think it's really, like if you don't feel

00:01:25.599 --> 00:01:30.279
conflicted about AI, that's weird.

00:01:30.279 --> 00:01:37.440
My kind of feelings of like existential dread kind of swing between mild and moderate, they're

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:41.760
kind of currently on mild at the moment, but I certainly do, it does feel like my kind

00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:46.680
of identities as a software engineer and a data scientist are under threat, and it's

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:51.480
very easy to feel kind of disempowered right now.

00:01:51.480 --> 00:01:56.120
So like one of the things I do, well one of the things I do that's not so helpful is I

00:01:56.120 --> 00:02:01.599
get drunk and like donate money to good causes, I'm not going to promote that as a strategy,

00:02:01.599 --> 00:02:06.239
but the other thing that I found really useful is just to try and do like one small thing

00:02:06.239 --> 00:02:08.679
to make the world a better place.

00:02:08.679 --> 00:02:12.639
So I like occasionally when I'm feeling particularly down, I'll just like go out and pick up some

00:02:12.639 --> 00:02:17.199
trash around my neighborhood, and that kind of reminds me like it's not my job to fix

00:02:17.199 --> 00:02:22.199
the world, all I can do is make my little bit of the world a little bit better.

00:02:22.199 --> 00:02:25.960
And so I kind of want to give you a bit of that today, I want to give you some ways that

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:32.199
you can engage with AI, with LLMs that hopefully like empower you and make you feel a little

00:02:32.199 --> 00:02:34.880
bit more in control of your future.

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:40.320
And so my two goals today are to give you a handful of useful skills, and to demystify

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:46.800
a few of the many, many, many jargony terms that come with AI.

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:51.559
I'm going to do this like mostly in R, using the Alma package.

00:02:51.559 --> 00:02:56.199
So Alma is a package that me and a few others at Pulsar have been working on recently.

00:02:56.199 --> 00:03:02.080
As you might kind of guess from the name, it's about using LLMs in R. And it has the

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:07.240
honor of being the first package name which I've created by adding vowels, rather than

00:03:07.240 --> 00:03:09.440
taking them away.

00:03:09.440 --> 00:03:14.000
So here's some Alma code, we're going to start by loading Alma obviously, and then I'm going

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.679
to create this chat object, here I'm using chat-anthropic, I'll show you a few other

00:03:18.679 --> 00:03:24.279
models today, but this is my kind of starting place, this is like my favorite model.

00:03:24.279 --> 00:03:28.279
And then I can interact with it, and I can interact with it from R in exactly the same

00:03:28.279 --> 00:03:34.320
way you can interact with it on the web.

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:40.039
I think one of the things that make LLMs so hard to reason about, or so hard to think

00:03:40.039 --> 00:03:45.800
about, is they kind of turn upside down, like what we think of as computers being good at,

00:03:45.800 --> 00:03:48.679
and what we think of as computers being bad at.

00:03:48.679 --> 00:03:53.639
Because you think of computers being good at multiplying numbers together, but it turns

00:03:53.639 --> 00:03:56.839
out that LLMs are pretty bad at multiplying numbers together.

00:03:56.880 --> 00:04:01.440
They'll certainly do their darnedest and get something that looks kind of right, but they'll

00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:04.080
be a little bit off.

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:06.559
In fact, they can't even count.

00:04:06.559 --> 00:04:13.559
So I asked this version of Anthropic, how many letters are in the word unconventional?

00:04:13.559 --> 00:04:18.239
And I won't make you think too much, it's actually four Ns, but Claude has confidently

00:04:18.239 --> 00:04:21.359
said two Ns.

00:04:21.359 --> 00:04:25.959
And then I asked it again, and it said there were three Ns.

00:04:26.079 --> 00:04:31.559
And then the cool thing about this being an R, well I ran that a hundred times, and fourteen

00:04:31.559 --> 00:04:37.519
times it said there was one N, seventy-six times it said there were two Ns, and ten times

00:04:37.519 --> 00:04:42.239
it said there were three Ns, so zero times it got it correct.

00:04:42.239 --> 00:04:46.079
This is a pretty easy problem.

00:04:46.079 --> 00:04:52.160
Now you might notice I've specified this model here, and that's because Claude fixed this

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:53.160
problem.

00:04:53.359 --> 00:04:58.480
So now if you ask Claude how many Ns are there in unconventional, it gives you the right

00:04:58.480 --> 00:04:59.480
number.

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:05.480
And this is not because the model has become more intelligent, this is because Anthropic

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:10.040
is embarrassed by the fact that its LLM can't count the number of letters, and has kind

00:05:10.040 --> 00:05:13.640
of adjusted their prompt to make it do this correctly.

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:17.799
And kind of interestingly, if you've been following any of the news about GBT's latest

00:05:17.799 --> 00:05:20.480
model, it has exactly the same problem.

00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:23.559
Like how many Bs in blueberry?

00:05:23.559 --> 00:05:31.640
This is like a simpler problem I think, it thinks there are three Bs rather than two.

00:05:31.640 --> 00:05:33.480
So LLMs kind of suck, right?

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:39.279
Like the results are stochastic, their models are constantly changing, the difference between

00:05:39.279 --> 00:05:46.000
good results and bad results can be razor thin, this kind of term of the jagged edge.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:51.279
But they always give kind of results that look plausible, and it's pretty unusual for

00:05:51.279 --> 00:05:55.359
them to say like, oh, I don't know, or like, this is just my best guess.

00:05:55.359 --> 00:05:58.920
Like they don't admit doubt or lack of knowledge.

00:05:58.920 --> 00:06:05.440
So I think all of those things are true, and LLMs can do things that computers kind of

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:06.440
could not.

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:10.920
We can ask them to write poems, like give me a limerick about the tidyverse.

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:15.320
A coder who worked with great zeal said tidyverse makes data feel real.

00:06:15.320 --> 00:06:21.119
With dplyr to wrangle and ggplot2's angle, my pipe dreams are now a good deal.

00:06:21.119 --> 00:06:24.959
Maybe not the best limerick in the world, but certainly a better limerick than I can

00:06:24.959 --> 00:06:28.519
come up with in five seconds.

00:06:28.519 --> 00:06:37.160
Or you can also use limericks to roast your colleagues, so I gave a talk at the JSM a

00:06:37.160 --> 00:06:41.200
couple of days ago, and I came up with a few roasts.

00:06:41.200 --> 00:06:44.119
I particularly like Roger, the one for Roger Ping.

00:06:44.119 --> 00:06:49.279
Roger believes in reproducibility, which is great, because his jokes and lectures reproducibly

00:06:49.279 --> 00:06:52.799
bomb every time.

00:06:52.799 --> 00:07:00.640
As Matt pointed out, you can of course combine the two, roast yourself with a limerick.

00:07:00.640 --> 00:07:06.519
And you can use LLMs to create art, and you can use them to make fun games.

00:07:06.519 --> 00:07:12.640
So I'm going to give you a live demo.

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:22.000
So I've asked it to create a fun quiz game that asks challenging questions about the tidyverse.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.320
So welcome to Tidy or Die!

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:31.559
Okay, so let's see, you have a data set called sales, and you want to keep only rows where

00:07:31.559 --> 00:07:33.720
the revenue column is greater than 1000.

00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:34.720
Which tidyverse function?

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:36.440
Okay, let's do a vote.

00:07:36.440 --> 00:07:38.720
So who thinks A?

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:41.040
Okay, who thinks B?

00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:42.880
Okay, who thinks C?

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:44.119
And who thinks D?

00:07:44.119 --> 00:07:47.279
Okay, let's say B.

00:07:47.279 --> 00:07:57.320
But that was way too easy.

00:07:57.320 --> 00:08:01.559
Okay, so let's do a nightmare question.

00:08:01.559 --> 00:08:05.440
I have to say, when it gets up to these really hard levels of difficulty, I'm like, yeah,

00:08:05.440 --> 00:08:06.440
this is totally wrong.

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:07.440
But we'll see how it goes.

00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:11.959
Okay, I want to fit a linear model predicting values from row number.

00:08:11.959 --> 00:08:16.279
Extract the R-squared value and then return a tipple with group and I, wow, okay.

00:08:16.279 --> 00:08:19.679
Which approach is most tidyverse elegant?

00:08:19.679 --> 00:08:22.200
Oh, yikes.

00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:50.039
I'm going to be like, hey, look, look, dude, I don't think we're getting this.

00:08:51.039 --> 00:08:57.520
I'm going to need shock silence, please.

00:08:57.520 --> 00:08:58.520
So it's fun, right?

00:08:58.520 --> 00:09:04.159
And you know, you can certainly use LLMs to stop learning about anything, but you can

00:09:04.159 --> 00:09:07.159
also use them to learn about things in new ways.

00:09:07.159 --> 00:09:11.119
Well, there's lots of other things you can do a little bit more practically.

00:09:11.119 --> 00:09:15.520
Here I'm going to take advantage of the first argument to chat anthropic, which is to provide

00:09:15.520 --> 00:09:17.200
a system prompt.

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:21.520
System prompt is not something you can really use when you're using a chat app on the web.

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:25.119
This is something that's going to set the tone for all of the following conversations.

00:09:25.119 --> 00:09:30.119
And I just say be terse here just so the answer will fit on one slide.

00:09:30.119 --> 00:09:35.200
But just to demonstrate that I think like one of the things that is like challenging

00:09:35.200 --> 00:09:39.200
about Google or search in general is if you know the name of the thing you're looking

00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:42.200
for, you can find out a ton of information.

00:09:42.200 --> 00:09:45.280
If you don't know what you're looking for, you can't.

00:09:45.359 --> 00:09:49.400
And kind of LLMs often give us that ability to say I'm kind of looking for this thing

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:53.159
that I vaguely remember, like it does something like this.

00:09:53.159 --> 00:09:54.159
And now you can get an answer.

00:09:54.159 --> 00:09:57.000
And I think that's tremendously empowering.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:03.080
Well, one thing that I did use recently as I was working on Hitter2 and I needed to add

00:10:03.080 --> 00:10:07.840
a new feature, I was like someone must have thought about this problem before.

00:10:07.840 --> 00:10:15.159
So I asked it, and really the key thing it told me about was this like leaky bucket algorithm.

00:10:15.159 --> 00:10:20.359
And that like algorithm and that metaphor was like so powerful and so useful, but there's

00:10:20.359 --> 00:10:26.080
no way, it would have been very, very difficult for me to discover that previously.

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:32.880
Or as sort of JD puts it succinctly, you know, like I think another thing that's challenging

00:10:32.880 --> 00:10:40.679
about LLMs is that they can be bad at simple things and good at complex things.

00:10:40.679 --> 00:10:44.840
And you can't just judge them, you can't just give up on them because they make these really

00:10:44.840 --> 00:10:46.960
silly mistakes and very simple problems.

00:10:46.960 --> 00:10:48.960
That's not really what they're designed for.

00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:54.039
They're designed to do things that computers are not traditionally good at.

00:10:54.039 --> 00:10:58.239
So again, my goal of this talk is to give you some useful skills and to demystify some

00:10:58.239 --> 00:10:59.239
jargon.

00:10:59.239 --> 00:11:02.799
So let's dive in to talk about three topics that I think are useful.

00:11:02.799 --> 00:11:08.919
The first are using LLMs to extract structured data, to turn all sorts of data into nice

00:11:08.919 --> 00:11:16.479
rectangles, talk a little bit about tool calling, which is a way to add extra capabilities

00:11:16.479 --> 00:11:21.520
to LLMs and to create interactive agents, and then we'll finally talk a little bit about

00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:25.960
how you can use LLMs to help you with your program.

00:11:25.960 --> 00:11:30.000
So I want you to kind of key this up, I want you to take a couple of seconds, just look

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:35.719
at this data here in a very simple vector, and I want you to think how would you go about

00:11:35.719 --> 00:11:39.840
extracting the name and age of each person.

00:11:39.840 --> 00:11:56.159
While you do that, I'm going to take a sip of water.

00:11:56.159 --> 00:12:01.640
So if you've ever collected data from humans, you've encountered situations like this.

00:12:01.640 --> 00:12:05.679
Mine was, I think, how there's like, how many people from Posit here?

00:12:05.679 --> 00:12:10.119
There's like eight people from Posit here, and Mine was saying that everyone put a different

00:12:10.119 --> 00:12:12.760
name for our company, Posit.

00:12:12.760 --> 00:12:15.559
Some different variation.

00:12:15.559 --> 00:12:19.359
And you know, if you look at this, like maybe you could come up with some regular expressions,

00:12:19.359 --> 00:12:25.640
like the age, you could use digits, but some people spelled it out, we've got the big 5-0.

00:12:25.640 --> 00:12:32.479
LLMs are even more hard, like names mostly are one words, but not always, they often

00:12:32.479 --> 00:12:36.080
start with a capital letter, but there's lots of other capital letters in there, so trying

00:12:36.080 --> 00:12:40.960
to do this deterministically with code is going to be really, really hard.

00:12:40.960 --> 00:12:44.919
But this is something that LLMs are generally pretty good at.

00:12:44.919 --> 00:12:47.919
And you can do this just using text.

00:12:47.919 --> 00:12:51.679
You can say, hey, extract the name and age from each sentence I give you, and I can give

00:12:51.679 --> 00:12:52.679
it a few sentences.

00:12:53.679 --> 00:12:58.039
And I won't expect you to remember, you'll just have to trust me that this is working

00:12:58.039 --> 00:12:59.039
correctly.

00:12:59.039 --> 00:13:03.880
And by and large, this is the sort of task that LLMs do like pretty reliably, they're

00:13:03.880 --> 00:13:09.080
not going to hallucinate because all the data's there, it's just finding the right thing.

00:13:09.080 --> 00:13:12.679
But wouldn't it be nice, like if rather than getting this string, which we're now going

00:13:12.679 --> 00:13:17.640
to need to pass in some way, wouldn't it be nice if we can get our data structure back?

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:19.479
Maybe something like this.

00:13:19.479 --> 00:13:22.039
Well, you can.

00:13:22.039 --> 00:13:26.599
And all you really need to do here is you need to give the LLMs a description of the

00:13:26.599 --> 00:13:30.880
schema, like exactly what do you want to get back from it.

00:13:30.880 --> 00:13:36.280
And here I'm saying I want an object, this is a JSON schema, this is kind of JSON's of

00:13:36.280 --> 00:13:40.359
the lingua franca of the web, and so this is what LLMs are pretty good at speaking as

00:13:40.359 --> 00:13:41.359
well.

00:13:41.359 --> 00:13:43.599
I want an object, which is like a named list.

00:13:43.599 --> 00:13:46.320
The name is a string and the age is a number.

00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:54.239
And now I can use this with chat structured instead of chat, and I get a nice list back.

00:13:54.239 --> 00:13:59.320
And I can do this to many prompts all at once in parallel using another LLMR function called

00:13:59.320 --> 00:14:01.119
parallel chat structure.

00:14:01.119 --> 00:14:05.239
And I think this is like a really cool little tool.

00:14:05.239 --> 00:14:12.479
I think this is like a data science superpower because you can now go from all sorts of unstructured

00:14:12.479 --> 00:14:18.119
data, not just text, but as I'll show shortly, images and video and audio, you can go from

00:14:18.119 --> 00:14:22.159
this unstructured data into nice rectangles.

00:14:22.159 --> 00:14:30.320
And if there's one thing that data scientists are good at, it's working with rectangles.

00:14:30.320 --> 00:14:32.440
So here's another little example.

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:36.880
Here I've got four images, and I'm going to say, well, I'll just give you a little bit

00:14:36.880 --> 00:14:37.880
of code.

00:14:37.880 --> 00:14:41.039
I'm going to find all of the files in the animals directory.

00:14:41.039 --> 00:14:45.320
I'm going to use this content image file function.

00:14:45.320 --> 00:14:48.880
That's how you tell Alma you want to send an image to the LLMs.

00:14:48.880 --> 00:14:50.280
I'm going to say what I want back.

00:14:50.280 --> 00:14:54.280
I want the animal and the background color, and then I'm going to call that same function

00:14:54.280 --> 00:14:55.280
again.

00:14:55.280 --> 00:14:59.299
And again, there's a little bit of stochasticity there.

00:14:59.299 --> 00:15:04.280
Like if I call this four times, I get four slightly different answers.

00:15:04.280 --> 00:15:07.559
But when you look at how they vary, this is kind of fair.

00:15:07.559 --> 00:15:10.440
Like what animal would you say this is?

00:15:10.840 --> 00:15:14.159
Like I think kitten and cat are both valid answers.

00:15:14.159 --> 00:15:15.159
What's the background?

00:15:15.159 --> 00:15:18.440
Well, I mean, it's kind of a beige-y gray.

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:24.159
So again, you're not going to get reliable, 100% reliable answers, but I think the problem

00:15:24.159 --> 00:15:28.960
here is that we have not been clear enough with exactly what we want.

00:15:28.960 --> 00:15:33.200
And I think the other thing that's interesting here is that once you've got that rectangular

00:15:33.200 --> 00:15:37.919
data frame, now you can use all of your statistical tools with it.

00:15:37.919 --> 00:15:42.440
And statistical tools don't assume that the data is measured without error.

00:15:42.440 --> 00:15:47.799
That assumption that there's going to be mistakes and variation and differences there is fundamentally

00:15:47.799 --> 00:15:48.799
baked into statistics.

00:15:48.799 --> 00:15:54.200
And I think this combination of structured data extraction and statistical modeling is

00:15:54.200 --> 00:15:59.080
super, super powerful.

00:15:59.080 --> 00:16:01.320
But of course, you're going to really want to think about that.

00:16:01.320 --> 00:16:03.559
You're going to think about like, is this the right prompt?

00:16:03.559 --> 00:16:05.799
Am I getting the right examples for that?

00:16:05.840 --> 00:16:11.960
If you want to do that in the LLM world, that's called evaluating your LLM, evaluating LLM.

00:16:11.960 --> 00:16:16.239
And Simon Couch, my colleague, has been working on the vitals package, if you want to make

00:16:16.239 --> 00:16:17.239
that a little bit easier.

00:16:17.239 --> 00:16:22.880
Simon's on the tidy models team, and so the goal is to really bring like what we know

00:16:22.880 --> 00:16:28.520
about evaluating statistical modeling, combine that with the state-of-the-art of evaluating

00:16:28.520 --> 00:16:32.760
LLMs, and to give you something that's like well-principled and well-thought-out.

00:16:36.640 --> 00:16:40.000
The next thing I want to talk about is tool calling, and I want to illustrate that with

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:41.479
a problem.

00:16:41.479 --> 00:16:43.239
Another thing that LLMs are bad at.

00:16:43.239 --> 00:16:49.479
If you ask an LLM what day it is today, best-case scenario, it's going to say, I don't know.

00:16:49.479 --> 00:16:56.840
If you ask this of chatGBT, it actually just makes up a date, which is not very reassuring.

00:16:56.840 --> 00:17:00.239
And LLMs like can't do anything, right, they're stuck in a box.

00:17:00.239 --> 00:17:05.760
You can't say, hey LLM, like delete the CSV files on my directory.

00:17:05.760 --> 00:17:11.839
And we can get around both of these limitations by using these things called tools.

00:17:11.839 --> 00:17:13.839
And a tool is actually something that's really simple.

00:17:13.839 --> 00:17:17.760
It's just a function along with some metadata.

00:17:17.760 --> 00:17:22.640
So I'm obviously going to write R functions, you can write them in any language, and then

00:17:22.640 --> 00:17:26.479
you're going to provide a little bit of metadata to tell the LLM when it might want to use

00:17:26.479 --> 00:17:27.479
that tool.

00:17:27.479 --> 00:17:33.040
So, for example, I can create a tool, this tool I've called today.

00:17:33.040 --> 00:17:37.280
It's going to call sys.date, which gives you today's date in R. I'm going to say what

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:42.880
it does, and I'm going to say what arguments it takes, which in this case is not.

00:17:42.880 --> 00:17:49.400
And now that I've empowered my chat, I can ask it what day is it today, and it can tell

00:17:49.400 --> 00:17:52.439
me.

00:17:52.439 --> 00:17:58.520
And when you look at this, you might be like a little surprised, like, is Anthropic like

00:17:58.520 --> 00:18:00.400
running R on their servers?

00:18:00.560 --> 00:18:05.520
That would be cool, but certainly a little surprising.

00:18:05.520 --> 00:18:07.359
That's not actually how tool calls work.

00:18:07.359 --> 00:18:12.760
So when you send or request the LLM, the LLM is going to be like, oh, okay, I recognize

00:18:12.760 --> 00:18:18.119
that I need to call this tool, and it's going to send that information back to you.

00:18:18.119 --> 00:18:22.439
That's going to get intercepted by Alma, and Alma is going to call the tool and return

00:18:22.439 --> 00:18:23.880
the result back.

00:18:23.880 --> 00:18:29.079
Now the LLM has all the information it needs to answer your original query.

00:18:29.079 --> 00:18:33.680
So the neat thing about this is because the code is running on your computer, you can

00:18:33.680 --> 00:18:38.680
do anything that you can do on your computer.

00:18:38.680 --> 00:18:42.719
So one thing you could do, for example, is to give the LLM kind of traditional computing

00:18:42.719 --> 00:18:43.719
powers.

00:18:43.719 --> 00:18:49.079
I could give it the power to multiply two numbers together, and now if I ask it to multiply

00:18:49.079 --> 00:18:55.959
two large numbers together, it can do that correctly because it's going to use that tool.

00:18:55.959 --> 00:19:02.479
And indeed, if you ask many of these LLMs on their websites to do these things, they'll

00:19:02.479 --> 00:19:06.760
just write a little bit of JavaScript code, because this is just another tool that they

00:19:06.760 --> 00:19:12.199
can use to answer the questions, and the models have been trained to know, or specifically

00:19:12.199 --> 00:19:16.680
the ones they kind of present on their websites, like don't try and do this stuff yourself,

00:19:16.680 --> 00:19:20.439
write a little program to do it.

00:19:20.439 --> 00:19:24.520
That brings me to one of the most powerful things you can do with tools, and that's to

00:19:24.520 --> 00:19:25.520
create an agent.

00:19:25.520 --> 00:19:30.319
So if you've read anything about AI on the internet lately, you've probably heard the

00:19:30.319 --> 00:19:37.520
term agent or agentic a million times, and you probably still have no sense of exactly

00:19:37.520 --> 00:19:39.839
what an agent is.

00:19:39.839 --> 00:19:44.359
But it turns out if you know what a tool is, and that's just a function plus some metadata,

00:19:44.359 --> 00:19:49.400
it's really easy to explain what an agent is, because an agent is just a chatbot that's

00:19:49.400 --> 00:19:51.800
been empowered with two tools.

00:19:51.800 --> 00:19:57.599
One that can read the state of the world, and one that can write the state of the world.

00:19:57.599 --> 00:19:59.119
So let's make an agent.

00:19:59.119 --> 00:20:07.079
I'm going to give my chatbot the ability to list all of the files on the current directory,

00:20:07.079 --> 00:20:11.219
and I'm going to give it the ability to delete files.

00:20:11.219 --> 00:20:15.319
And now I can say, hey, delete all the CSV files in the current directory.

00:20:16.319 --> 00:20:19.680
It's going to say, well, okay, to do that, I'm going to need to find out what files are

00:20:19.680 --> 00:20:21.239
in the current directory.

00:20:21.239 --> 00:20:28.359
So it runs, it requests that Alma call LS, Alma is going to return the results back to

00:20:28.359 --> 00:20:29.359
the LLM.

00:20:29.359 --> 00:20:34.839
It's going to say, okay, I found two CSV files, A and B, I'm going to delete those.

00:20:34.839 --> 00:20:39.400
It's going to send that tool call request back to Alma, Alma is going to delete the

00:20:39.400 --> 00:20:44.819
files, and now it's deleted those files on my computer.

00:20:44.819 --> 00:20:49.020
And hopefully when you look at this, you're like, Hedley, what on earth are you thinking?

00:20:49.020 --> 00:20:56.180
You have just empowered an LLM, which is notoriously unreliable, to delete files on your computer.

00:20:56.180 --> 00:21:01.500
And certainly you can put a few guardrails around it, and there are some sort of built-in

00:21:01.500 --> 00:21:06.060
to the LLMs if you ask it to delete all the files on your computer.

00:21:06.060 --> 00:21:10.300
The model itself is going to be like, that's a bad idea, I'm not going to do that.

00:21:10.619 --> 00:21:16.219
Basically, this is the state of security today with agents.

00:21:16.219 --> 00:21:20.500
It's the YOLO model.

00:21:20.500 --> 00:21:26.660
And I think discovering ... so agents are interesting because they offer so much potential.

00:21:26.660 --> 00:21:31.339
You can empower an LLM to do anything, and so much danger.

00:21:31.339 --> 00:21:34.900
You've now empowered an LLM to do anything.

00:21:34.900 --> 00:21:39.020
And it's going to take us, I think, collectively quite some time to figure out how to do this

00:21:39.020 --> 00:21:40.020
safely.

00:21:41.020 --> 00:21:46.140
So that brings me to my third topic, which is using LLMs to code.

00:21:46.140 --> 00:21:51.060
I want to talk about ... I'll sort of first center you into what the main techniques for

00:21:51.060 --> 00:21:53.099
using LLMs to code are.

00:21:53.099 --> 00:21:55.339
Hopefully you've seen many of these before.

00:21:55.339 --> 00:21:57.219
The first one is kind of the most basic.

00:21:57.219 --> 00:22:02.459
You just go into chatgpt.com and say, hey, give me a function that does blah, or I need

00:22:02.459 --> 00:22:05.260
to write some R code that solves this problem.

00:22:05.260 --> 00:22:10.140
That's kind of fine, but you're constantly copying and pasting back and forth.

00:22:10.140 --> 00:22:14.979
This is kind of like the old days, like pre-markdown, where you're copying and pasting the results

00:22:14.979 --> 00:22:18.339
from Excel into your Word document, and something changes.

00:22:18.339 --> 00:22:23.900
Constantly copying things back and forth, and it's very, very easy to get out of sync.

00:22:23.900 --> 00:22:31.140
So now most modern IDEs are starting to bring in AI tooling through either inline autocomplete,

00:22:31.140 --> 00:22:36.219
so that's just when you start typing, and the LLM helpfully sometimes, and not so helpfully

00:22:36.219 --> 00:22:39.619
most of the time, suggests finishing your thought.

00:22:39.619 --> 00:22:47.540
I think one of the skills of programming today is being able to ignore that when it's bad,

00:22:47.540 --> 00:22:50.540
and accept it when it's good.

00:22:50.540 --> 00:22:53.739
You can also have chat that's inside your IDE.

00:22:53.739 --> 00:22:55.619
This is just sort of a convenience.

00:22:55.619 --> 00:23:00.619
It's exactly the same thing as chatting with chatgpt, but you don't have to copy things

00:23:00.619 --> 00:23:01.619
back and forth.

00:23:01.619 --> 00:23:05.780
You can just kind of click a button, and the chat knows more about what you're doing because

00:23:05.780 --> 00:23:08.900
it can see what you're working on.

00:23:08.900 --> 00:23:12.579
And then finally, kind of the newest trend is agentic coding.

00:23:12.579 --> 00:23:18.099
This is things like a cursor or clawed code, where the LLM is just going to go off and

00:23:18.099 --> 00:23:19.300
do a bunch of work.

00:23:19.300 --> 00:23:25.819
It's going to write some code, it might write some tests, run those tests, and iterate for

00:23:25.819 --> 00:23:28.380
a little while.

00:23:28.380 --> 00:23:33.939
And so I want to talk about, there's lots of ways in which LLMs do pretty useless and

00:23:33.939 --> 00:23:37.619
horrible things when coding, but I want to talk about the things that I think are clear

00:23:37.619 --> 00:23:38.619
wins.

00:23:38.619 --> 00:23:39.619
And there are two.

00:23:39.619 --> 00:23:42.920
And the first clear win, I think, are translations.

00:23:42.920 --> 00:23:46.900
So whenever there's all of the information the LLM kind of needs there, it just needs

00:23:46.900 --> 00:23:51.140
to be expressed in a different form, they tend to do pretty well.

00:23:51.140 --> 00:23:56.660
So if you can really accurately write in pseudocode what you're trying to do, LLMs are going to

00:23:56.660 --> 00:24:00.140
turn that into code in any language pretty reliably.

00:24:00.140 --> 00:24:05.859
One thing I use it for, often websites give you a curl command that you run on the console,

00:24:05.859 --> 00:24:09.260
you can ask an LLM to translate that to header 2 code.

00:24:09.260 --> 00:24:14.979
Or you can convert your LaTeX docs to Corto, you can convert your SQL to dplyr, you can

00:24:14.979 --> 00:24:20.660
convert your SASS to R code, you can convert your words to regular expressions.

00:24:20.660 --> 00:24:24.739
Like many of these things, it's going to get correct a lot of the time, and even when it

00:24:24.739 --> 00:24:30.900
doesn't, just having that first shot of a translation can be really, really useful.

00:24:30.900 --> 00:24:36.099
And I want to show you, kind of finish with like one kind of cool example from my colleague,

00:24:36.099 --> 00:24:38.420
that my colleague George came up with.

00:24:38.420 --> 00:24:45.859
So I'm going to take a screenshot of this shiny app that George drew, and I'm going

00:24:45.859 --> 00:24:52.099
to pop open Positron Chat, and I'm going to drag the screenshot in, and I'm going to be

00:24:52.180 --> 00:24:59.540
like, please, oops, please make this into a shiny app.

00:24:59.540 --> 00:25:04.020
And actually I need to stop running this shiny app I was running earlier, so let's do that first.

00:25:04.020 --> 00:25:10.819
Okay, please make this into a shiny app.

00:25:10.819 --> 00:25:15.300
And it's certainly writing shiny code much faster than I can write shiny code.

00:25:15.300 --> 00:25:16.300
Is it any good?

00:25:16.300 --> 00:25:18.819
Well, we'll find out in a couple of seconds.

00:25:18.819 --> 00:25:28.500
So now I'm just going to click run, I'm going to see this shiny app.

00:25:28.500 --> 00:25:34.660
It's not done a very good job, actually.

00:25:34.660 --> 00:25:37.859
So this is one of these stochastic things that's certainly done better in the past,

00:25:37.859 --> 00:25:41.060
but you can see it's got the basic idea of the shiny app, right?

00:25:41.060 --> 00:25:45.380
It's got the variable, it's got a distribution, the distribution is not very useful because

00:25:45.380 --> 00:25:47.219
it only offers one thing.

00:25:47.219 --> 00:25:54.300
So we could say, let's go back to my chat, and be like, could you add box plots plus

00:25:54.300 --> 00:26:01.219
frequency polygon plus density plot?

00:26:01.219 --> 00:26:06.420
To say one thing I particularly like about LLMs is I don't have to worry about correcting

00:26:06.420 --> 00:26:10.140
my spelling mistakes so I don't look like an idiot.

00:26:10.140 --> 00:26:12.219
Let's see how it does.

00:26:12.219 --> 00:26:16.300
I'm just going to quickly go back and cancel that shiny app.

00:26:16.300 --> 00:26:17.300
Oops.

00:26:17.300 --> 00:26:20.300
Go back to my chat.

00:26:20.300 --> 00:26:23.300
Okay, well, that's not very useful.

00:26:23.300 --> 00:26:27.819
Let's take a try again.

00:26:27.819 --> 00:26:28.819
Just write it.

00:26:28.819 --> 00:26:29.819
Don't edit it.

00:26:29.819 --> 00:26:36.819
Oh, I think the problem is I had this edit mode on, which I didn't want.

00:26:36.819 --> 00:26:37.819
Let's see.

00:26:37.819 --> 00:26:40.819
Okay, there we go.

00:26:40.819 --> 00:26:50.819
It's churning away.

00:26:50.819 --> 00:26:53.819
Let's see how it's done.

00:26:53.819 --> 00:27:06.619
It's done a pretty good job for a first pass.

00:27:06.619 --> 00:27:11.339
And that kind of brings me to the other area where I think LLMs give you a clear win, which

00:27:11.339 --> 00:27:15.300
maybe this is not the best name, but I kind of think of this as like lowering activation

00:27:15.300 --> 00:27:20.300
energy, where you can just do something very, very quickly.

00:27:20.300 --> 00:27:26.420
It might not be super correct or perfect, but it gives you something.

00:27:26.420 --> 00:27:29.979
Maybe that's a quick demo or prototype that you can kind of look at and be like, oh, okay,

00:27:29.979 --> 00:27:30.979
this is cool.

00:27:30.979 --> 00:27:31.979
That's not cool.

00:27:31.979 --> 00:27:33.939
It gives you some immediate feedback.

00:27:34.260 --> 00:27:40.500
Maybe it's something that's just so awful, like you feel compelled to fix this.

00:27:40.500 --> 00:27:43.380
This is something that I find useful for writing.

00:27:43.380 --> 00:27:47.579
I'll ask it to write about something, not because I think it's going to do a good job,

00:27:47.579 --> 00:27:52.420
but because I know it's going to do a bad job, and then I feel compelled to correct

00:27:52.420 --> 00:27:53.420
it.

00:27:53.420 --> 00:28:00.140
This kind of reminds me of one of my strategies back in the old day of the I help mailing

00:28:00.140 --> 00:28:01.140
list.

00:28:01.339 --> 00:28:07.260
Sometimes you ask a question and it's just crickets, like no one cares to answer.

00:28:07.260 --> 00:28:12.020
So instead of asking a question, you just state something confidently, and you know

00:28:12.020 --> 00:28:17.780
if you're wrong, someone will dive in and correct you.

00:28:17.780 --> 00:28:21.939
The other thing I've been using it for lately is just, I've been working on test that.

00:28:21.939 --> 00:28:27.660
There are issues there that have been lingering for four or sometimes longer years, because

00:28:27.660 --> 00:28:30.739
I'm like, oh, this is going to be a lot of work.

00:28:31.339 --> 00:28:34.739
And so I've just been throwing flawed code at it, I'm just like, take a stab.

00:28:34.739 --> 00:28:38.900
And sometimes it comes up with an answer, and I'm like, oh, that problem actually wasn't

00:28:38.900 --> 00:28:44.420
that hard after all, this has all been in my head this whole time.

00:28:44.420 --> 00:28:48.979
Also super great, like if you're working in an unfamiliar area, whether that's a new programming

00:28:48.979 --> 00:28:55.500
language or a new package or a new domain, LLMs get you good enough to be dangerous,

00:28:55.500 --> 00:28:59.339
for better or worse, very, very quickly.

00:28:59.339 --> 00:29:02.859
And I think, and Claude actually came up with a pretty good summary of this, which

00:29:02.859 --> 00:29:08.979
is, I think, LLMs can make the cost of trying so low that you attempt things you'd normally

00:29:08.979 --> 00:29:12.420
postpone, avoid, or never get around to.

00:29:12.420 --> 00:29:15.300
And I think this is like a pretty compelling use case.

00:29:15.300 --> 00:29:19.819
Like you're not going to want to trust everything it produces, but you're now, like you've gotten

00:29:19.819 --> 00:29:24.579
unstuck, you're moving forward, sure it's going to make mistakes, but you're going to

00:29:24.579 --> 00:29:25.579
learn from those.

00:29:26.579 --> 00:29:32.699
So I'm going to sum up, I feel like you can't really give a talk about LLMs without talking

00:29:32.699 --> 00:29:35.660
about some of the many, many, many concerns.

00:29:35.660 --> 00:29:41.979
I think the first kind of concern is the cost and the quality of access.

00:29:41.979 --> 00:29:48.500
I will say, I'd really encourage you to sign up for an API key, put $5 on it, and just

00:29:48.500 --> 00:29:53.420
see how far that takes you, because it takes you a surprisingly long amount.

00:29:53.420 --> 00:29:56.939
The LLMs are getting cheaper and cheaper and cheaper, and you can do quite a lot of

00:29:56.939 --> 00:29:59.739
cool stuff for only $5.

00:29:59.739 --> 00:30:06.760
Also, fortunately, Google's Gemini model is kind of in a distant third place, and so Google

00:30:06.760 --> 00:30:11.699
is just spending cash like anything to try and get to make it popular, and that means

00:30:11.699 --> 00:30:16.900
it's got a very generous free tier right now, so you should take advantage of it.

00:30:16.900 --> 00:30:19.900
By and large, I think local models are not worth it.

00:30:19.900 --> 00:30:24.819
They can be in general, but if you're just getting started with LLMs, start with something

00:30:24.819 --> 00:30:31.459
that's much more likely to give you positive results, which is Anthropic, OpenAI, or Gemini.

00:30:31.459 --> 00:30:37.540
I think another concern, like I genuinely, genuinely, genuinely believe you should care

00:30:37.540 --> 00:30:40.979
about the environment, you should worry about climate change, you should think about how

00:30:40.979 --> 00:30:48.339
much water and electricity you're conserving, you're using, but if you have flown on a plane

00:30:48.339 --> 00:30:53.819
in the last 12 months, that just blows away by orders of magnitude any environmental impact

00:30:53.819 --> 00:30:55.859
of your GPT usage.

00:30:55.859 --> 00:30:59.260
So while I think it kind of makes sense, unlike, you know, we need to think about this on a

00:30:59.260 --> 00:31:05.859
societal level, the actual impact of an individual chat GPT query is very, very small, and you

00:31:05.859 --> 00:31:11.420
should be thinking about other ways to save water and power.

00:31:11.420 --> 00:31:14.819
Also lots of concerns about data privacy around LLMs.

00:31:14.819 --> 00:31:20.619
I think this is sort of surprisingly something that affects you more as an individual.

00:31:20.619 --> 00:31:27.060
If you're in a large company, basically every large company, all of their data already lives

00:31:27.060 --> 00:31:34.020
on Azure or GCP or AWS, like all of the data's already in the cloud, all the LLM models are

00:31:34.020 --> 00:31:36.219
running in the same cloud.

00:31:36.219 --> 00:31:42.099
Most large enterprises do not have these concerns because basically, you know, these big companies

00:31:42.099 --> 00:31:46.300
already technically have access to all of their data, but there's lots of protection

00:31:46.300 --> 00:31:48.859
in place to make sure it's not getting misused.

00:31:48.859 --> 00:31:52.819
So something you should think about as an individual, certainly if you're working with,

00:31:52.819 --> 00:31:57.260
you know, any confidential data, you need to be very, very cautious about sending it

00:31:57.260 --> 00:32:05.819
to these models, but most businesses can negotiate, you know, things with, negotiate contracts

00:32:05.819 --> 00:32:11.699
with these providers that ensure that your data is not going to be used to train future models.

00:32:11.819 --> 00:32:16.219
Finally, the kind of the biggest concern I have, which I don't have a good answer for,

00:32:16.219 --> 00:32:18.219
is like evil billionaires.

00:32:18.219 --> 00:32:24.540
I feel like I'm becoming increasingly radicalized that billionaires shouldn't exist, but definitely

00:32:24.540 --> 00:32:27.540
a concern.

00:32:27.540 --> 00:32:34.540
So again, to kind of come back to my first point, like if you are feeling like disempowered

00:32:34.540 --> 00:32:39.739
or out of control, or you like you don't understand how like AI and LLMs are going to affect your

00:32:39.780 --> 00:32:46.380
future life, I'd really encourage you to just do one little thing, do one little experiment

00:32:46.380 --> 00:32:49.459
that helps you kind of understand what's going on.

00:32:49.459 --> 00:32:51.500
I think you'll find that empowering.

00:32:51.500 --> 00:32:57.459
I think you'll learn that while there's lots of hype around models replacing data scientists

00:32:57.459 --> 00:33:01.739
and software engineers, we're a very, very long way from that happening in practice.

00:33:01.739 --> 00:33:06.579
They're very good at some things that can be very useful and empowering tools, but it's

00:33:06.579 --> 00:33:10.260
a long way from replacing our jobs.

00:33:10.260 --> 00:33:16.140
The other thing I will say that I'm a little tempted to do is to do a little best defense

00:33:16.140 --> 00:33:21.979
as a strong offense, and really like if you're worried about your job being replaced by AI,

00:33:21.979 --> 00:33:27.260
it feels like managers are way more vulnerable to being replaced by AI, because so much of

00:33:27.260 --> 00:33:30.780
what a manager does is just summarize the information that they receive from multiple

00:33:30.780 --> 00:33:32.459
channels and report it out.

00:33:32.459 --> 00:33:39.780
So feel free to go on the attack at people higher up in your company.

00:33:39.780 --> 00:33:44.420
So in summary, I kind of showed you three areas where I think LLMs are kind of particularly

00:33:44.420 --> 00:33:46.979
interesting and empowering today.

00:33:46.979 --> 00:33:54.819
Use structured data to turn unstructured data, text, images, audio, video, into rectangles.

00:33:54.819 --> 00:34:00.339
Then you can apply all of your rectangle skills that you already have.

00:34:00.339 --> 00:34:04.380
Tools are a really neat way to extend the capabilities of LLMs.

00:34:04.380 --> 00:34:06.660
Tools are just functions plus metadata.

00:34:06.660 --> 00:34:08.679
You already know how to write functions.

00:34:08.679 --> 00:34:14.219
You can now extend LLMs to do whatever you want, including creating agents that do really

00:34:14.219 --> 00:34:17.179
dangerous and stupid things.

00:34:17.179 --> 00:34:22.979
And then finally, LLMs like super, you know, sometimes super amazing at coding, sometimes

00:34:22.979 --> 00:34:27.300
super terrible at coding, but I think the two areas where they give the kind of clearest

00:34:27.300 --> 00:34:34.060
wins today are translations, like whenever you have expressed an idea clearly in one

00:34:34.060 --> 00:34:39.260
language or one image, you can translate that to another tool.

00:34:39.260 --> 00:34:44.580
And lowering the activation energy, giving you the ability to experiment, to try out,

00:34:44.580 --> 00:34:49.820
to expand into new areas where you don't know so much about.

00:34:49.820 --> 00:34:50.820
Thank you.

00:34:50.820 --> 00:34:51.820
Thank you.

00:34:51.820 --> 00:34:52.820
Thank you.

00:34:52.820 --> 00:34:53.820
Thank you.

00:34:53.820 --> 00:34:53.820


